AnalysisGoals:
For this project, we will test the hypothesis that the embryonic neural crest microenvironment can reprogram the metastatic phenotype of neuroblastoma. We will determine whether invasive neuroblastoma expression recapitulates neural crest migration and whether the embryonic neural crest microenvironment can reprogram the metastatic expression profile.

The project has the following analysis goals:
1) Determine differentially expressed genes between 6 human neuroblastoma cell lines.
2) Determine gene expression changes resulting from overexpression or knock down of TRKB expression.
3) Identify gene expression changes resulting from exposure to the embryonic neural crest microenvironment.
4) Determine the expression profile of wild type and TRKB-perturbed neural crest derivatives during embryonic development.
5) Compare the expression profiles of wild type and TRKB-perturbed neural crest derivatives with neuroblastoma transplanted into the embryonic microenvironment.

For this project, we will test the hypothesis that the embryonic neural crest microenvironment can reprogram the metastatic phenotype of neuroblastoma. We will determine whether invasive neuroblastoma expression recapitulates neural crest migration and whether the embryonic neural crest microenvironment can reprogram the metastatic expression profile.

The project has the following analysis goals:
1) Determine differentially expressed genes between 6 human neuroblastoma cell lines (MOLNG-1660).
2) Determine gene expression changes resulting from overexpression or knock down of TRKB expression in neuroblastoma cell lines.
3) Identify gene expression changes resulting from neuroblastoma cell line exposure to the embryonic neural crest microenvironment.
4) Determine the expression profile of wild type and TRKB-perturbed neural crest derivatives during embryonic development (MOLNG-1687).
5) Compare the expression profiles of wild type and TRKB-perturbed neural crest derivatives (MOLNG-1687) with neuroblastoma transplanted into the embryonic microenvironment.

The purpose of this bulk RNA-seq experiment is to identify genes regulated by agat-1/2/3 in intact animals and after amputation. I expect the downstream targets of agat-1/2/3 to be differentially expressed after injury in the negative control, but not so in the agat-1/2/3 (RNAi) conditions. I also aim to identify any differences in downstream target genes among agat-1/2/3 at homeostasis and after amputation. Therefore, questions I hope to answer include:
-	Which genes and signaling pathways are regulated by agat-1/2/3 in intact animals?
-	Which amputation-induced genes are regulated by agat-1/2/3?
-	Do agat-1, agat-2, and agat-3 regulate the same genes and signaling pathways or do they have unique targets?
